                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.94/476½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum Prepared in the War Department</hi>
                    <note n="84" xml:id="d711fn84">Copy transmitted to the Department by the War
                        Department.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian"
                        notAfter="1940-10-22T17:00:00-05:00" notBefore="1940-10-21T18:00:00-05:00"
                        >undated</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>On October 11, 1940 the Japanese Ambassador in Washington<note n="84a"
                        xml:id="d711fn84a">Kensuke Horinouchi.</note> advised the Foreign Office in
                    Tokyo as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>In the future, as long as we do not pay any attention to the
                            anti-Japanese attitude of the United States, I do not think that at this
                            time the United States will take any directly aggressive attitude toward
                            us. I think this is clear. President Roosevelt and Secretary of State
                            Hull are both withholding comment on the alliance and as long as they do
                            not make hostile action against us, we should awe them by our very
                            silence, steadily consolidating our new order in the Far East. This, I
                            believe, would be the best plan.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
        </body>
